properties.name: Community Information
properties.location: Coast - Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for for coastal water from Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border.

  • The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to below safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and ocean is now safe for recreational contact with the water.
  • It is important to note that advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood remains in place.
  • The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis.
Do not eat prawns from affected waters.

These prawns may have come from the Gippsland Lakes and Ninety Mile Beach area and may contain toxins from the recent blue green algae bloom.

Do to not consume prawns caught within 10 nautical miles of the shore between Mcloughlins Beach and the Victoria-New South Wales border.
What you should do:
  • Visit betterhealth.vic.gov.au for more information. 
  • Keep up-to-date with algae information at www.water.vic.gov.au/waterways-and-catchments/rivers-estuaries-andwaterways/blue-green-algae 

Protect your health:
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 19/10/2022 03:40 pm or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.

  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for The Castle Creek Catchment..
  • MAJOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT EUROA.
  • MAJOR FLOODING WILL EXTEND TO KIALLA WEST FROM SATURDAY MORNING.
  • Major flooding is occurring in the Seven and Castle Creeks, with major flooding occurring at Galls Gap Road and Euroa. 
  • Flooding will extend downstream, with major flooding likely at Kialla West by Saturday morning.
  • Rainfall has eased, and upstream locations have peaked.  
Castle Creek:
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Castle Creek at Telfords Bridge
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. If in low lying areas or near waterways move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • For information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides – be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Latrobe River

Flood Watch for Northern and parts of Southern Victoria

MINOR TO MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING OR EXPECTED ACROSS SEVERAL VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS

A cold front is crossing Victoria with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.

Rainfall totals of 10-90 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.

Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring across Northern Victoria. Moderate to major flooding is expected in the Werribee and Maribyrnong catchments respectively. Moderate flooding is likely for parts of Western Victoria. Isolated Minor flooding is possible in parts of Gippsland.

Catchments likely to be affected include:
Mitchell River
Macalister River
Thomson River
Latrobe River
South Gippsland Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch and Act message is being issued for Violet Town.

  • Honeysuckle Creek at Violet Town is likely to reach flood level similar to October 1993.    
  • There will be extensive inundation through Violet Town on Thursday night due to overflows from Honeysuckle Creek and Lambing Gunyah Creek. 
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

This flood may be similar to 1993, which resulted in:
  • Most of the town being affected. with floodwater coming from from Honeysuckle and Lambing Gunyah creeks.
  • Forty houses between Murray Street and High Street flooded to 1.2 metres deep.
  • Eighteen people being evacuated.
  • The Catholic Church, Masonic Hall, nine businesses and the Bush Nursing Centre affected.
  • Water spilled over the railway line into Railway Street, Cowslip Street and Lily Street.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 09:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Broken River Benalla to Casey Weir 
- Major flooding is likely along the Broken River Benalla to Casey Weir.  It is currently at 2.63 metres and rising, with moderate flooding. 
- The Broken River at Casey Weir is likely to reach the major flood level (3.00 m) late Friday morning 


An Evacuation Warning remains in place for parts of Benalla.

This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 3:44 AM, Friday 14/10/2022. 

Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Acheron River. 

MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG THE ACHERON RIVER, YEA RIVER, HUGHES CREEK AND SUNDAY CREEK

Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday.

Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. Major flooding is occurring along the Acheron River, Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek.

Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday morning, with further rises to the moderate and major flood levels during Saturday. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Acheron River:

Major flooding is occurring along the Acheron River.

The Acheron River at Taggerty peaked at 3.27 metres around 03:00 am Friday 14 October and is currently at 3.14 metres and falling. The Acheron River at Taggerty is likely to fall below the major flood level (3.00 m) Friday morning.

This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 8.08pm Thursday 13/10/2022.
People in low lying areas should move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.

Do not attempt to drive through floodwaters - it could be the last decision you make.
What you should do: 
Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

  • MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT CHARLTON TOWN DURING SATURDAY MORNING
  • MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT QUAMBATOOK FRIDAY MORNING
  • MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG THE AVOCA RIVER AT YAWONG WEIR, CHARLTON TOWN AND QUAMBATOOK
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Avoca River at Yawong Weir, Charlton Town and Quambatook. Moderate flooding is expected Friday afternoon at Charlton Town, with major flooding likely from Saturday morning. Moderate flooding is possible at Quambatook during Friday morning as the floodwaters from last week's rainfall arrive.
Avoca River to Charlton Town:
Major flooding is likely along the Avoca River to Charlton Town. The Avoca River at Charlton Township is currently at 4.14 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Avoca River at Charlton Township is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (5.90 m) Friday afternoon. The river level is likely to reach the major flood level (7.50 m) Saturday morning. Further rises are possible.
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.

  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Upper Murray Catchment.

MINOR TO MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING OR EXPECTED ACROSS SEVERAL VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS
A cold front is crossing Victoria with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards.
Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.
Rainfall totals of 10-90 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.
The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Find local flood information and practical advice about how to prepare at www.ses.vic.gov.au 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.webBody:
This Flash Flood Watch and Act is being issued for Beaufort. 

  • Heavy rainfall is causing localised flash flooding in Beaufort. 
  • You can stay safe by avoiding flooded and low-lying areas. 
  • Floodwater can be very deep, rise quickly and move fast. 
  • Be aware that heavy rainfall may also increase the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
If you are located in Beaufort, you are in danger. You should immediately move indoors, away from floodwater. Do not enter floodwater.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are inside: 
  • Stay inside and be aware of rising floodwater. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

If you are outside: 
  • You should stay away from trees, drains, low lying areas, creeks, canals, culverts and floodwater. 
  • You should seek shelter indoors, away from floodwater. 

If you are driving: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

You should stay informed by listening to local emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Many homes have become isolated by floodwater.
  • Flash flooding has impacted the Western Highway at Beaufort, King Street, Neil Street, Havelock Street, Willoby Street, High Street, Albert Street and Leichardt Street
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update will be issued as the situation changes.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.


MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR, WHERE FLOOD LEVELS HAVE PEAKED EARLY FRIDAY MORNING

MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT SHEPPARTON FROM SATURDAY EVENING

Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday.

Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. Major flooding is occurring along the Acheron River, Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek.

Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday morning, with further rises to the moderate and major flood levels during Saturday. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:

Major flooding is likely along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 9.67 metres and rising with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Murchison is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (10.20 m) Friday afternoon. River rises will continue into the weekend, and the river level is likely to exceed the major flood level (10.70 m) Friday night.

The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 9.31 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to exceed the minor flood level (9.50 m) late Friday morning. The river level is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (10.70 m) Saturday morning and is likely to reach the major flood level (11.00 m) Saturday afternoon. Further rises are expected as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek
 and replaces the warning issued yesterday for the same event. 

  • A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Regional Roads Victoria has undertaken geotechnical investigations at the site and implemented traffic management measures limiting Bogong - High Plains Road to one lane in this area, with reduced speed also in place.
  • With heavy rainfall forecast for the region this week and into next week, a full closure of Bogong - High Plains Road is in effect from midday on Wednesday 12 October. 
  • From now, access to and from Falls Creek will only be allowed for emergency services and essential services. 
  • When the road will re-open has not been determined and will depend on weather conditions and ongoing management of the landslide risk.
  • Regional Roads Victoria will continue to monitor the landslide risk and potential impact on Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Geotechnical experts will complete assessments of the site and determine the best course of action to address the risk
Stay safe by avoiding fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads and the area in general. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide.

The Bogong High - Plains Road at Bogong IS NOW CLOSED from Mt Beauty as planned from midday on Wednesday 12 October in anticipation of poor weather worsening the landslide.

Road users can no longer enter or exit Falls Creek or the Bogong Village from either direction on the Bogong High - Plans Road. 

What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, expect to be unable to leave for three days until the extreme weather has passed and the road is safely cleared. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landside occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, powerlines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Driving:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
  • There is now no access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong - High Plains Road is closed. 
  • The Bogong High Plains Road on the other side of Falls Creek remains closed due to snow and will likely remain that way for several more weeks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#viclandslide).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Broken River downstream of Casey Weir. 

Moderate Flooding likely at Orrvale during Friday with major flooding possible overnight Friday.

Strong river rises are occurring in the Broken River and its tributaries upstream of Benalla. Minor flooding is expected at Orrvale from late Friday morning, moderate flooding from Friday afternoon and major flooding possible from overnight Friday.

In the 24 hours to 5:00 am Friday, widespread rainfall totals up to 110 mm have been observed across the Broken River catchment. Rainfall is expected to ease from Friday morning.

Broken River downstream of Casey Weir
  • Major flooding may occur along the Broken River downstream of Casey Weir. 
  • The Broken River at Orrvale is currently at 4.44 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. It is expected to exceed the minor flood level (6.80 m) late Friday morning. 
  • The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (7.20 m) Friday afternoon and may reach the major flood level (7.90 m) overnight Friday into Saturday

An Emergency Warning remains current for the Broken River at Benalla.

This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 4:19 AM, Friday 14/10/2022. 
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.

At the Minor (6.8m) and Moderate (7.2m) Flood Levels
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • The Midland Highway east of Shepparton may be affected flooding
  • Rural properties upstream of Doyles Road may become flooded
  • Gordon Drive (Broken River anabranch) may be over-topped at the western end by waters flowing out of Lake Kialla.
  • Lake Amaroo may over top and Kialla Lakes Drive becomes affected by flooding

Above the Moderate (7.2m) to the Major Flood Level (7.9m)
  • Some properties may experience over-floor flooding at Archer Road, Kialla West
  • Gordon Drive is likely to be closed
  • Innundation of land in Hooper Rd, Kialla
  • Water over the Northern Causeway on Archer Street
  • Further over-floor flooding on Doyles Road and Jamieson Road, Jamieson Road likely to be closed
  • Archer Road, south of Kialla Lakes Drive, may be over-topped by overflow from Broken River anabranch
  • Residents north and east of Lake Kialla and east of Lake Amaroo may become isolated. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Clunes.

Creswick Creek in Clunes is rising as a result of continuing significant rainfall. 

Properties in the following areas are may be impacted by flooding:
  • Blackmores Rd
  • Clunes Caravan Park
  • Fraser Street
  • Purcell street
  • Ligar Street
  • Cameron Street
  • West Parade

Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 09:40 am or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon Weir to Kerang. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) CAIRN CURRAN
  • MAJOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAANECOORIE RESERVOIR OVERNIGHT THURSDAY INTO FRIDAY AND MAY REACH 7.7 m FRIDAY MORNING (EXCEEDING 2011 PEAK OF 7.5 m)
  • MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR AND APPIN SOUTH
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in parts of the Loddon River, with renewed rises from overnight rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream through the catchment. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.
  • Major flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran and expected at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie Reservoir from overnight Thursday into Friday. Moderate flooding has is occurring along the Loddon River at Appin South. The Loddon River Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is steady around the moderate flood level.
  • Further heavy rainfall is forecast for into Friday.
Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.
  • The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 3.12 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.10 m) during Thursday and into Friday.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is currently at 76.7 (m AHD) metres and rising slowly, below the minor flood level (77.00 m AHD). 
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is expected to remain below the minor flood level (77.00 AHD m) during Thursday. 
  • Further river level rises are likely as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 07:00 am or as the situation changes.

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

Flood Watch for Northern and parts of Southern Victoria 

MINOR TO MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING OR EXPECTED ACROSS SEVERAL VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS

A cold front is crossing Victoria with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.

Rainfall totals of 10-90 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.

Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring across Northern Victoria. Moderate to major flooding is expected in the Werribee and Maribyrnong catchments respectively. Moderate flooding is likely for parts of Western Victoria. Isolated Minor flooding is possible in parts of Gippsland.

Catchments likely to be affected include:
Mitchell River
Macalister River
Thomson River
Latrobe River
South Gippsland Rivers

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Barnadown to Rochester. 

  • This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 5:33pm. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN JAN 2011 FLOOD EVENT EXPECTED ALONG THE CAMPASPERIVER
  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG THE CAMPASPE RIVER AT BARNADOWN
  • MAJOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT ROCHESTER TOWN FROM EARLY FRIDAY MORNING
  • Rapid and significant river level rises are occurring along the Campaspe River and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday. Major flooding is occurring at Barnadown with river levels still rising. 
  • River levels are expected to exceed those experienced during the January 2011 flood event at both Barnadown and Rochester Town.
  • Goulburn Murray Water advises that Lake Eppalock is full and spilling. 
  • River levels at Downstream (D/S)Lake Eppalock are around the major flood level and rising. 
Campaspe River Barnadown to Rochester
  • Major flooding is expected along the Campaspe River Barnadown to Rochester.
  • The Campaspe River at Rochester Town is currently at 112.66 metres AHD and rising, below the minor flood level. 
  • The Campaspe River at Rochester Town is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (114.00 mAHD) overnight Thursday into Friday. The river level is expected to reach the major flood level (114.50 mAHD) early Friday morning and is likely to reach around 115.50 metres AHD overnight Friday into Saturday.Further rises are possible.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Heavy rainfall overnight has resulted in significant runoff and flooding in local creeks and streams. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 05:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT COROWA, TORRUMBARRY AND STEVENS WEIR

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Kiewa River and the releases from Hume Dam, renewed minor flooding is possible at Albury from Friday.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

Downstream along the Murray River, moderate flooding continues at Corowa and Torrumbarry. Major flooding is likely at Barham from Thursday afternoon. Floodwaters from the Murray River combined with floodwaters from the Edward River have caused minor flooding at Wakool Junction and may cause minor flooding at Boundary Bend from early next week. Minor flooding is possible at Wentworth around the end of October.

Along the Edward River, moderate flooding is occurring at Stevens Weir. Minor flooding continues at Deniliquin and Moulamein.

Further rainfall is forecast from the rest of Thursday into Friday which may cause renewed rises. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided as required.

Severe Weather Warning for heavy rainfall is current for Riverina Districts which covers Murray and Edward River catchments.

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Corowa. Renewed minor flooding is possible at Albury. Minor flooding is possible at Yarrawonga.

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Kiewa River the Murray River at Albury may reach the minor flood level (4.30 m) Friday morning.

The Murray River at Corowa peaked around 6.21 metres on Sunday 09 September and is currently at 5.99 metres and falling slowly with moderate flooding. Subject to the inflows from the Kiewa River renewed river level rises are possible at Corowa. Predictions will be provided once the upstream peak levels are observed.

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Ovens River, the Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream may reach the minor flood level (6.40 m) during Monday.

Subject to tributary inflows the Murray River at Tocumwal may reach the minor flood level (6.40 m) over the weekend..
  • Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
  • Most of the flooding impacts are occurring on the NSW side of the Murray River
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria.  
  • For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria  
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, tracks and campgrounds maybe closed due to flooding
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Ovens River to Bright.

Moderate Flooding likely along the Ovens River from Friday.

Minor to Moderate flooding is likely to develop along the Ovens River from early Friday. Further rises are possible. 

After heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday, rainfall in the Ovens River catchment has eased in the last few hours.

Ovens River to Bright
  • Moderate flooding may occur along the Ovens River to Bright. 
  • The Ovens River at Bright is currently at 2.57 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. It is likely to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) late Friday morning. 
  • The river level may reach the moderate flood level (3.60 m) later during Friday.

This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 2:17 AM, Friday 14/10/2022. 
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground if still safe to do so.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you will be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
Between Harrietville and Bright
  • Flash flooding may result  from local rainfall on the bushfire -affected catchment of East Branch with “breakout” flows downstream (north) of Feathertop Lane. 
  • The first part of the Great Alpine Road to flood in this area is often at “Frosty Corner” (north of Harrietville near the trout farm) which isolates Harrietville.
  • At Stony Creek, flooding over the Stony Creek Bridge isolates properties in Stony Creek Rd, Pinchgut Lane and Millers Track.
  • At Freeburgh, flooding over the Freeburgh Bridge isolates residents in Old Harrietville Rd, Snowy Creek Rd and Caloutas Lane.
Bright area 
  • Bright can be isolated by floodwaters due to flooding of the Great Alpine road Road at Wabonga Lane near Eurobin  and at Stoney Creek / Frosty Corner between Bright and Harrietville.  
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Hopkins River.

  • MINOR TO MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING OR EXPECTED ACROSS SEVERAL VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS
  • A cold front is crossing Victoria with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards.
  • Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.
  • Rainfall totals of 10-90 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.
  • Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring across Northern Victoria. Moderate to major flooding is expected in the Werribee and Maribyrnong catchments respectively. Moderate flooding is likely for parts of Western Victoria. Isolated Minor flooding is possible in parts of Gippsland
  • The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.

Incident Location: Hopkins River
Issue Date: Thursday 13 October 2022, 02:15 pm
Next Update: Friday 14 October 2022, 03:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/22725/moreinfo

This Flood Watch is being issued for Hopkins River.

- MINOR TO MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING OR EXPECTED ACROSS SEVERAL VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS
- A cold front is crossing Victoria with heavy falls likely as the front moves slowly eastwards.
- Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.
- Rainfall totals of 10-90 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.
- Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring across Northern Victoria. Moderate to major flooding is expected in the Werribee and Maribyrnong catchments respectively. Moderate flooding is likely for parts of Western Victoria. Isolated Minor flooding is possible in parts of Gippsland
- The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required. 



Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.

MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT SHEPPARTON FROM SATURDAY EVENING.

Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday.
Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. 
Major flooding is occurring along the Acheron River, Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek.
Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday morning, with further rises to the moderate and major flood levels during Saturday. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:
River level rises are likely along the Goulburn downstream of Shepparton from early next week. The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 8.23 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain below the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Friday. River level rises are expected over the weekend upstream floodwaters arrive.  


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.  
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Fifteen Mile Creek.

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South.

After heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday, rainfall in the Ovens River catchment has eased in the last few hours.

Fifteen Mile Creek
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Fifteen Mile Creek. 
  • The Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South peaked at 5.80 metres around 03:30 am Friday 14 October and is currently at 5.52 metres and falling. It is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (4.20 m) Friday morning

This Watch and Act (Moderate Flood Warning) replaces the Watch and Act (Major Flood Warning) issued at 2:18 AM, Friday 14/10/2022. 

Major Flooding is no longer expected along the Fifteen Mile Creek.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area:
At the Moderate Flood Level (4.2m)
  • Above floor flooding is not expected at this level
  • Along the Three Mile Creek, shallow flooding commences north of the Hume Freeway over low lying farmland, Gravel Pit Rd, and the South Wangaratta Industrial area including Tone Road near the GOTAFE paddocks and the CFA/SES Training Ground.
  • Around the One Mile Creek, Rattray Ave footbridge will be closed and low-level flooding is likely along roads and land in other areas including Swan and Bronmar Streets.

A number of roads may be affected by flooding and may be closed including:
  • Snow Road, between the Hume Freeway and Laceby-Targoora Road
  • Greta Road near corner of Brian Higgins Drive impacting access to the airport from both north and south
  • Arundels Lane
  • Tone Road, at 3 Mile Creek
  • Clarkes Lane
  • Gravel Pit Road
  • Glenrowan Road

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Plenty River.

Plenty River:

The Plenty River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 46 mm since 09:00 AM Thursday 13 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 1-5 mm is forecast for the catchment Friday 14 October 2022.

Water levels of the Plenty River at various locations are rising in response to the rain.

The level of the Plenty River at Lower Plenty is currently at 4.70 metres and rising, below the Minor Flood Level (5.0 metres). It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (5.0 metres) this morning (Friday 14 October 2022).

Minor flooding in the Plenty River catchment is expected to affect low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway.

The river heights at 07:16 AM Friday 14 October 2022 were:
Plenty River at Mernda: 3.95 metres, steady
Plenty River at Greensborough: 4.84 metres, rising
Plenty River at Lower Plenty: 4.64 metres, rising

properties.name: Evacuate Now
properties.webBody:
If you live, work, or are holidaying in Wedderburn you should evacuate now.

  • The Skinners Flat Reservoir is likely to breach
  • This will result in approximately 3ft of strong fast moving waters from the Skinners Flat Reservoir through the Wedderburn Township via the Calder Highway and out towards Wedderburn Junction Road
If you are located in the highlighted Wedderburn area, it is strongly recommended that you evacuate now.

  • There is a relief center open at the Wedderburn Hall that residents should evacuate to as soon as possible
  • If the Skinners Flat Reservoir has already been breached at the time of receiving this message, cease evacuation and shelter towards the back of your house for approximately 1 hour, or until the water subsides
  • DO NOT ENTER THE FLASH FLOOD WATERS. IT IS DANGEROUS
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include:
  • A relief centre that has been opened at the Wedderburn Hall, 28 High Street, Wedderburn. 
  • The home of family or friends who live in a safe location, away from flash flooding.

The safest evacuation route is by the Calder Highway.

When you leave remember to take your pets on leads and in cages, your mobile phone, chargers and medications.

If you are travelling by car:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • For road closure information go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or call 131 170.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive through floodwater.

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Shelter in the highest location possible.

This warning is current to 14/10/2022 04:00 am. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Evacuation of homes is required.
  • Flash flooding is likely to affect Wedderburn, and houses near the Skinners Flat Reservoir
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 04:00 am or as the situation changes.

Evacuation information: 
  • Go to Victoria Police Community Evacuation Information.
  • For information on what to do with your pets go to agriculture.vic.gov.au/pets/care-and-welfare/pets-and-emergencies.
Emergency contacts: 
  • For life threatening emergencies phone Triple Zero (000).
  • For flood and storm emergency assistance from the SES phone 132 500.
Stay informed: 
  • Go to www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Phone the VicEmergency Hotline to talk to someone about this warning on 1800 226 226 (freecall).
  • People who are deaf, hard of hearing, or who have a speech/communication impairment can contact VicEmergency Hotline via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, phone the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VicEmergency Hotline. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the VicEmergency app or follow VicEmergency on Twitter (#vicfloods) or Facebook.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Echuca. 
  • Coliban Water, following consultation with the Department of Health, advises that customers in Echuca should boil their drinking water until further notice.   
  • This advisory has been issued following excessive stormwater due to inclement weather entering one of our treated water storage tanks. 
  • This may compromise the safety of the drinking water. The tank has now been isolated.
  • Coliban Water will keep customers informed as the situation changes. 
If you are live or work within Echuca, you must boil tap water before drinking.
What you should do:

  • Coliban Water recommends customers should bring water to a rolling boil before being used by heating the water until a continuous and rapid stream of air bubbles is produced from the bottom of a pan or kettle. 
  • Kettles with automatic cut-off switches are suitable. Variable temperature kettles should be set to boil.     
  • After heating, water must be allowed to cool before using it, and be stored in a clean, closed container for later use. 
  • Care should be taken to avoid scalding injuries especially around children.       
Boiled water can be used for:  
  • Drinking  
  • Preparing beverages  
  • Washing and preparing food  
  • Preparing baby formula  
  • Brushing teeth  
  • Making ice.  
Unboiled water can be used for:
  • Washing your hands
  • Showering and bathing
  • Flushing toilets
  • Washing dishes (ensure dry before use)
  • Clothes and garden watering. 
Ensure water is not ingested whilst bathing.  

  • Consumption of unboiled water can cause gastro-like symptoms. If you experience any of these symptoms, please contact your GP and inform your GP of this advisory.  
  • Please share this advice with neighbours and friends in the affected area. 
  • Would owners of rented properties please ensure your tenants are aware of this advisory.
Impacts in your area:
  • If a water quality issue is detected, Coliban Water will work to address the issue and keep customers informed.
This message was issued by the Department of Health.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks to Euroa. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT EUROA.
  • MAJOR FLOODING WILL EXTEND TO KIALLA WEST FROM SATURDAY MORNING.
  • Major flooding is occurring in the Seven and Castle Creeks, with major flooding occurring at Galls Gap Road and Euroa. 
  • Flooding will extend downstream, with major flooding likely at Kialla West by Saturday morning. 
  • Rainfall has eased, and upstream locations have peaked
Seven Creeks to Euroa:
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks to Euroa.
  • The Seven Creeks at Euroa peaked at 5.60 metres around 02:30 am Friday 14 October, just below the level of 5.67 metres recorded in October 1993. 
  • The Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 5.42 metres and falling with major flooding. 
  • The Seven Creeks at Euroa is likely to remain above the major flood level (4.60 m) Friday morning
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.    
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Don’t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Rochester. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • Floodwaters are rapidly rising. 
  • Major flooding is expected to impact Rochester on Friday morning from 3am, with the Campaspe River expected to peak on Friday afternoon.
  • The river is expected to start rising from Thursday night.
  • The duration of the flood event is likely to be between seven and 10 days.
  • This is an update, replacing the Emergency Warning issued at 7pm.
If you are located in Rochester, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at at Echuca United Football Netball Club at 252 High Street Echuca. The facility may have capabilities for small domestic pets, preferably in cages.
  • Family or friends’ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
Rochester Hospital and Aged Care Facility will utilise the hospitals of Echuca, Shepparton, Bendigo and Castlemaine.

Northern Highway is the most accessible route, but continue to check regular updates via the VicTraffic website.

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
This warning is current to Thursday 10pm. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency.
  • For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Evacuation of homes is required.
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate is dangerous and may put your life at risk.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Local schools have been closed until further notice pending floods to prevent people outside Rochester attending the community.
This flood may be similar to 2011, where 80 per cent of Rochester and its surrounding rural areas flooded. In this flood:
  • More than 250 properties had water above floor level with many people and properties isolated by floodwater.
  • Businesses in the town were impacted with most of the shops flooded.
  • Public areas near the Campaspe River were flooded and remained closed due to the risks of falling trees.
  • Many roads, community facilities and private properties were damaged.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 07:30 am or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

EMERGENCY WARNING - RIVERINE FLOOD - Evacuate Immediately
Incident Location: Rochester
Issue Date: Thursday 13 October 2022, 10:37 pm
Next Update: Friday 14 October 2022, 07:30 am

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/22868/moreinfo

This Emergency Warning is being issued for Rochester. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

- Floodwaters are rapidly rising. 
- Major flooding is expected to impact Rochester on Friday morning from 3am, with the Campaspe River expected to peak on Friday afternoon.
- The river is expected to start rising from Thursday night.
- The duration of the flood event is likely to be between seven and 10 days.
- This is an update, replacing the Emergency Warning issued at 7pm.


        If you are located in Rochester, it is   recommended you Evacuate Immediately.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Flash Flood Watch and Act is being issued for the Heathcote Township. 

  • Flooding is impacting the Heathcote Township.
  • You can stay safe by avoiding flooded and low-lying areas. 
  • Floodwater can be very deep, rise quickly and move fast. 
  • Be aware that heavy rainfall may also increase the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
If you are located in the Heathcote Township, you may be affected by flooding.
It is safest to stay indoors, but if flooding is impacting your house there is a relief center open at the Heathcote R.S.L in High Street that is staffed tonight.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are inside: 
  • Stay inside and be aware of rising floodwater. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

If you are outside: 
  • You should stay away from trees, drains, low lying areas, creeks, canals, culverts and floodwater. 
  • You should seek shelter indoors, away from floodwater. 

If you are driving: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters 91.9 - Star FM, and monitoring warnings. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Some homes and buildings could be flooded. 
  • Power, water, sewerage and telephone services could be lost in the area. 
  • Some roads or bridges have been closed. 
  • For road closure information or report road hazards, call VicRoads 13 11 70, check the VicTraffic website (https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/), or contact your local council.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.   

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
